description.text:
I really like my MakerFarm printer, but even after tightening belts etc... I'd still have some ringing in the X direction. My theory was that the two screws which are used to attach the belt to the carriage were acting as springs (because attached only at one end). So I made this little part to tweak this mechanism. It goes over the back of the carriage instead of the first nut (it does need a slightly longer M3 screw). This allows the pivot point for the belts to be supported on both ends.

It fixed the (small) amount of ringing I had left in my printer but YMMV. ;-)

description.text: Top cap of the handle of a Ford Transit (1992) sliding door.

Should easily print parts on most printers.  Should also be usable right off the hot plate.

Everything you require is in the picture with all things laid out. Here is a quick list:
--- 4-40 1.25" Screws, 2x

  • Print the two pieces. I recommend a minimum of 5% fill on the GoPro base and 20% fill on the clamp. The nuts are meant to be snug, so you may need to trim a bit if your printer is out of tune.   • Assemble the items (see pictures). Once you assemble the clamp for the first time, it should be self-retaining and doesn't ever have to be removed.

description.text:
The blinds in our conservatory have been up a while and the sunlight and heat have taken their toll of the plastic runners, causing several to simply disintegrate.

So, either buy a new set of blinds or casually say to the wife 'If I print replacement parts, the 3d printer has actually saved us money.'

These are replacement sliders for vertical blinds into which you pop the gears from the old, broken sliders. There's also a replacement hangar bit as these seem to suffer from the heat and sunlight too.

Remember to draw out how the old strings, springs, gears, washers, connectors etc. were put together so you can easily reassemble everything at the end.

All the sliders on all our blinds look the same, despite being from different manufacturers, so in my house at least these replacements are 'universal'. If they don't fit your blinds though, sorry!

Clean up

Carefully poke out the support material, especially from the tiny slot at the top, where the linking spring goes. There's not much plastic to resist heavy hands.

You'll need to pop out the cogs from the old gearboxes - that's easy as they are nylon and still in good shape. Popping them into the newly printed parts takes courage, but be firm and they'll squeeze in.

You'll probably have to gently straighten the hook ends of the link springs with pliers to slot them into the new bits. Then simply bend them back. My springs withstood two or three iterations of this without breaking, but your mileage might differ.
Designed in Sketchup from scratch using vernier calipers and imagination.

A mouthpiece and mold for making a silicone blowpipe adapter are coming soon. I won't hate any other thingers for beating me to the punch on these...

Protips:

Again, it's not going to seal very well, so you'll have leaking air pressure. You'll have to blow/suck a bit more with this than you would a brass swivel. It works well, but isn't optimal.

I like to add a bit of superglue to the outside edge of the mating surfaces of the two cube halves.

The first prototype I glued one barb to the cube and "sealed" it on with superglue to see if it would seal better.... Marginal success; try it if you really want, but it didn't do too much for me...

It's not a terrible idea to install one of the hose barbs into your blowhose prior to gluing the assembly together...

This is a more advanced version of my trapezoid Edge puzzle.

This video shows the finished puzzle.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jKdSOPCc_M4

This puzzle has the internal mechanism of a 3x3x5, but the layers are offset to create a shapeshifting puzzle that is very challenging to solve.

In addition to the printed pieces (Print each piece as many times as the x# specifies) you will also need the core and hardware from a YJ Guanlong. I'm sure other cores could work, but Guanlongs cost $3-4 and you get the core plus springs and screws that you will need. I find it well worth the price to not have to find small springs and screws that fit otherwise.

I highly recommend sanding all the surfaces inside and out to a smooth finish. This is not only for looks, but also to ensure the best operation of the puzzle.

description.text:
I had a carbon monoxide detector that I needed to hang. I could have taken the simple route and pounded a couple of nails into the wall but I thought it might be fun to complicate things.

Actually, I just didn't want holes in my wall.

I got myself a variety pack of 3M Command strips. This hanger is designed to neatly cover the adhesive portion of a small Command strip - about 16mm x 23mm.

Don't expect this to hold much weight! The carbon monoxide detector is quite light and hangs on two of these things so they are overkill for the purpose. That said, if you try to hang a picture on one, you are liable not only to pull the hanger off the adhesive strip but to break the post of the hanger as well.

Given you want good adhesion with the strip, you will want a very smooth back. Print directly on glass (perhaps with glue stick if you don't have a heated bed) and clean with rubbing alcohol both on the mount and the wall to ensure no grease is there to thwart adhesion.

This should be an extremely simple print overall. No supports are required! Make sure you have adequate part cooling near the top or just dial back your speed to ensure the post cools adequately as it is printed, instead of getting knocked around by the hot end.

description.text:
A modified version of donnyb99's great tensioner design. As some mentioned in the comments, the alignment of the pulley ends up raising the belt a little causing misalignment of the belt path and rubs against the v-slot aluminum extrusion. This remix drops the pulley to avoid this misalignment and some other minor changes for better fit (at least on my machine).

You will need a M5x25 hex head bolt and matching nut to install in puller and a M4x25 socket cap bolt and matching nut to mount pulley in puller. I originally used a nylon lock nut on the M5 bolt and have recently come into a situation where tightening/loosening the nut has put enough torque on the bolt head to strip the nut trap in the puller part. Not sure if standard nuts would help in avoiding that or not.

I installed this without disconnecting the belt from the carriage, which requires removal of the belt from the stepper gear and once the tensioner is installed you can roll the belt over the stepper gear, eg putting a chain on your bicycle sprocket. Once the belt is back in place, apply tension with knob (pic shows just a nut).

title: Taz 6 Heatsink Fan Duct with LEDs

description.text:
This design addresses two pet peeves I have had with the Taz 6: The heatsink fan is right smack in the middle of where you want to be looking to see what the printer is doing, and all the fans around the head put the print head in shadow.
This puts a 45 degree bend in the fan duct that gets the fan up and to the left, getting it out of the line of sight. It also adds two LED mounting points to allow you to wire up some LEDs to light up the print head.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 6

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm layers, 0.5mm nozzle

Infill:

Does not matter

Notes:

My first print of this was with 0.4mm layers. The slope of the funnel was too steep and loops of filament fell into the duct. With 0.3mm layers, it prints fine.
You probably want to print this with a high temperature plastic like ABS or nGen since part of this is very close to the hot end of the extruder.

The LEDs are optional

The LED mounting points can be deleted by change the value of "EnableLEDMount" to false.
If you choose to add the LEDs, you will need high brightness white 5mm LEDs. For example, this part will work: https://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/tt-electronics-optek-technology/OVLEW1CB9/365-1177-ND/827113
For this type of LED, the flat side of the base/short lead is the negative lead.
You will also need a current limiting resistor sized to get you the proper operating current for the LEDs. For this example, I was using the 5V supply that powers the heatsink fan. The forward voltage drop of the LED is 3.2V that leaves 1.8V across the current limiting resistor. Using Ohm's Law: V=I*R where V=5-3.2=1.8V and I=0.02A, you can solve for R and find that you need a 90 Ohm resistor in series with the LED to get 0.02A from a 5.0V supply.
I put six holes in the mount to allow you to put some 0.1" diameter resistors and/or wires through the holes.
The 5V supply is not large enough to allow you to run the two LEDs in series, so you must have a current limiting resistor for each LED, and run the two LED circuits in parallel.
I tapped into the power by creating a power tap adapter in series with the Extruder cable. This way I did not need to cut any cables, and the extruder can be reverted back to the original condition. You can make such an adapter by soldering the following parts back to back and soldering wires to pins 9 and 10 at the junction to pick up 5V (9 is 5V, 10 is the return).
https://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/on-shore-technology-inc/302-S161/ED10523-ND/2794234
https://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/te-connectivity-amp-connectors/535542-8/A115378-ND/663725

Even if you don't want the LEDs, four brass threaded inserts are necessary to mount the fan: https://www.mcmaster.com/#catalog/123/3329/=18ce4bf
(In case it is not obvious from the link, the part number you are looking for is 94180A331)
I cleaned up my soldering iron, set it at the lowest temperature, stuck one of these on the end and slowly pushed it into the hole. Let it cool, then trim off the plastic that squeezed out.

title: Power Cord mod for Snap Together Mini Lamp

description.text:
Create a working Mini Lamp!

I loved Makerbot's Snap Together Mini Lamp
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:27062
It's cute but I thought there was something to be added...

A thin USB cable or an old mouse cord can be fed through the base to the shade as shown in the photos.
The bulb is from (the Original!) Mattraption's https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:26920

If you're feeling adventurous, a sketch of the LED circuit is attached and some assembly notes below. If you find the notes or drawing are gibberish, just skip that and print the bulb with Glow-in-the-Dark filament.

P.S. The ball was created by easports1059 at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1129417

Printer:

Da Vinci 1.0a Repetier

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Print "Lamp_Snap_Luxo" and "Arm_Parts_Snap_Luxo" from Makerbot's Snap Together Mini Lamp at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:27062
Print the "Power Cord Base" and the two "Connector" parts here.
For best quality, I printed two of each "Connector" part together. I don't have a cooling fan and this allows each layer to cool before the next one arrives.

The bulb is from Mattraption's https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:26920

LED Option: Translucent filament with 0% infill and no top or bottom perimeters.
Glow-in-the-Dark option: 30% infill, usual top and bottom perimeters.

The lamp in the photos is printed in ABS but your own favourite material should work just fine.

Electronic Parts List

1 x LM317L Voltage Regulator
3 x white LED, 60mA, 3.2-4V
1 x 20R resistor
1 x 30R resistor
1 x small push switch
1 x thin USB cable or old mouse cord
misc. pieces of shrink tube
big gob of hot glue

Light it up!

A sketch of the circuit is attached.
There are only 4 active components. An LM317L in constant current configuration drives 3 white LED's in parallel. The 20 ohm resistor sets the current at 60mA, the 30 ohm resistor sets the LED voltage at 3.3V.

Despite the short component list, assembly and fitting of the parts inside the lamp is a challenge. If you are not comfortable with a soldering iron (it's hot!), you may want to go with the Glow-in-the-Dark lightbulb option mentioned above.

Thread the USB cable through the assembled lamp. The components are soldered directly together onto the switch with shrink tubing for insulation. The LED's go inside the bulb, I used a small cable tie to secure the LM317L to the switch. Smother the regulator and resistors in hot glue around the switch and the base of the bulb. Mount inside the shade.

Plug in and turn on.
If you're lucky, there WILL be light.

The printed parts were hacked together on Tinkercad.

The circuitry was cobbled together with the aid of the LM317L data sheet
http://www.ti.com/lit/ds/snvs775k/snvs775k.pdf
and an example from http://www.homemade-circuits.com/2013/06/universal-high-watt-led-current-limiter.html
The LM317L is a "light-weight" version of the LM117 or LM338 that only handles up to 100mA. The resistor values have been set to deliver 60mA at 3.3V to the LEDs.
(Note: If you are looking at the sample circuit, the control voltage for the LM317L is 1.2V, not 1.25V as used for the LM117.)
The math says you could add a fourth LED and drop the 20 ohm control resistor to 18 ohms for an 80mA supply, YMMV.

title: Rear Spool Holder and Filament Guide for Da Vinci 1.0a printers

description.text:
Rear spool holder and filament guide for easy filament changes. The lid can be fully opened with filament in place. No cutting or drilling of the case required.

Simple, functional design inspired by NickJallday's factory slot spool holder.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1174205

Both internal and external spools can be loaded at the same time for faster filament changes.

Tested on the Da Vinci 1.0a, should fit most of the 1.x and 2.0 models.
I've been using this spool holder for about 6 months and finally realized it was working well, robust and ready to post.

The filament guide allows the filament to pass through the gap between the case and the lid while protecting the filament when the lid is open. The simple hook on the spool holder means it can be attached and removed while standing in front of the printer. Similarly, a groove helps to guide the filament through the hole without having to move the printer (or climb over it) to see where it goes.

A short length of PTFE tubing is required to protect the guide from wear. (Hint: recycle the original Da Vinci guide tube).

The "short" spool holder should be OK for spools up to about 60mm (2.25") wide.
The larger spool holder will deal with spools up to about 100mm (4") wide.

Feedback and suggestions are very welcome. If it works for you, please post a "make" of your print. It's great to know your work is making someones life a little easier! :-).

Printer:

Da Vinci 1.0a Repetier

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

30%+

Notes:

Designed and tested in ABS for strength and durability though most materials (PLA, PETG, etc) should be fine. Print as oriented in the .stl's for maximum strength.

A brim or raft may help bed adhesion when printing the filament guide.

Supports ARE REQUIRED for for the filament guide.
DO NOT use supports for the spool holder, it has internal structure for strength and stiffness.

Carefully remove the support material from the filament guide. Go lightly when working on the locating slot, a piece of hacksaw blade might help to cut it out if your slicer is as over-enthusiastic as mine with the supports. (Slic3r v1.29)

Be careful not to remove the small bump on the end of the guide closest to the filament hole. It's meant to be there and keeps the guide in place. Without it you will have endless frustration fishing the guide from the depths of the internal filament bay!

After cleaning out any supports, insert a short length of Teflon tube into the guide hole from the inside of the filament guide until it is flush with the rear of the guide. I recommend recycling a piece of the original Da Vinci PTFE tubing as it has a larger internal diameter than standard Bowden tube and creates less drag on the filament.

You may find it easier to remove the lid when first installing the filament guide. It will only fit in one spot and will be aligned with the existing guide tube or a Bowden extruder mounted in the pre-drilled location in the frame. I have to admit that it is optimised for the e3d Titan that can just be seen in the photos.

It's a thing!

I'd been intensely jealous of a friend's Phantom 3, and my wife was aware of my interest in the field of quadcopter piloting. I'd resigned myself to building one entirely but my wife bought me a Syma X5SW for my birthday.
I had a good bit of fun flying it around as it is actually a rather enjoyable craft for the money, but knew eventually (as she did) that I would have it apart for upgrades.
Thus, here it is.

I went with a Cleanflight board as I'd seen some videos of quad kits using cleanflight firmware and the configuration interface really seemed intuitive and well-designed. As such I purchased a board designed by the lead developer of the CleanFlight software.
A bit of research later, and I have the motor control board, flight control board, transmitter and receiver, and voltage regulators ordered.
Upon disassembly of the X5SW, I found the stock mounting bracket post spacing too small, and the chassis post spacing too wide for the board I purchased.
Thus this was born. 2 design revisions resulting in something that you can literally just snap a flight controller onto for testing, and then screw down for permanence. (I'll work on allowing for vibration dampening another time?)
The screw post spacing was a pain, tolerances were tight and FDM printers dislike multiple small-diameter posts with typical settings. I've included my settings in the Thing post, YMMV of course.

NOTES:
Possible issue when slicing - when using Makerbot Print, posts on one side tend to print solid up to the thinner section of the post, making screwing the caps down basically impossible. YMMV.
I got around that by heating a very thin metal rod up and inserting it into the hole at the top of the post, using the heat to smooth the interior layers so screwing the board down doesn't just cause the top of the post to just pop off.

Designed in SketchUp, for better or worse.

description.text:
I remixed paxamime's Digital Gauge Dial Adaptor https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2334149 to allow a mechanical dial gauge to fit it (the gap for the gauge was widened to 6mm) and I have raised the dial clamp such that it can be fitted to the X-Axis Rails when the Z-Axis is in the home position.

I've widened it by 5 mm to help make it rigid. I suggest it is printed with 50% or greater infill because the bolt and nut holding the Dial Gauge will create a considerable causing force and my previous prints started to deform over time.

I printed it in eSUN's PETG filament but any filament should work fine.

Using the gauge:

A) Home the Printer
B) Attack the adaptor so it is measuring the front-left corner of the bed
C) Adjust that corner of the bed to the correct height (based on an 0.003 mm feeler gauge)
D) Zero the gauge to this height
E) Move the bed forwards and adjust back-left corner, until the gauge reads zero
E) Check and adjust the front and back corners until a minimum difference from zero is obtained
E) Remove the adaptor and attach it again on the far side of the X-Rails
F) Repeat the steps above

I quite often find that the two left hand corners need a final tweak as well after adjusting the right ones.

If you are not using glass for your bed, you may find you have to compromise on the accuracy when levelling the bed.

Run a test print. If the bed position needs adjusting make these by eye and then re-zero the gauge and relevel the bed.

Once set to a working distance, the gauge can be used again and again without having re-zero it. To guarantee the gauge stays in position, I've used two nuts so that they lock together.

I'll make a video of how to do this soon and add it to my new YouTube Channel:

TurbulantCalm's Adventures in 3D Printing.

I love the way the adaptor looks a little like a zombie Bart Simpson...

Making a wavy flag

To make the flag "wavy", I followed these steps. Do so at your own risk because it involves very hot water to bend the finished print.

BE CAREFUL WITH HOT WATER IN THE FOLLOWING STEPS.

CAUTION: DON'T TRY TO MOVE A PLATE FULL OF HOT WATER!!!

I filled a microwave safe plate with just a few millimeters of water, then boiled the water in the microwave for about 35-45 seconds.

Leaving the plate in the microwave, I carefully used a pair of tongs and placed the finished print in the boiled water for just a few seconds, then fished it back out with the tongs.

I let it cool for a second or so then I used my hands to mold a simple wave in the flag.

You should probably use a pair of rubber gloves.

description.text:
This is a simple part to set up the correct nozzle to bed thickness taking only a few minutes to print it is a quick and accurate method to level the bed to the correct nozzle gap.
Print these disks near to each of the adjustment screws at 0.2mm layer height (Disk is 0.2mm thick) measure the disk and then adjust the screw to correct, reprint, measure and adjust again to verify, Repeat as necessary.

Although it is show below for the Wanhao it is also suitable for other printers, I have a WDi3+ and an Ultimaker2.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

100%

Notes:

These Disks hep to finely adjust the gap between the nozzle and the print bed, use this after the initial adjustment with the card or paper method.

Creating the print file;
Place this disk in your slicer, place one close to each of the adjustment screws as well as one in the bed centre.
Slice at a thickness of 0.2mm with the normal settings, (No raft or Supports) the total print time is only a couple of minutes. I suggest you save it as "BedLeveling" or similar.

Print the file and adjust the bed;
Run the print file, once finished gently remove the front left disk, measure the thickness and then adjust the bed screw to compensate to achieve a 0.2mm thickness.
repeat for the other adjustment screw positions.
the centre disk is just a final check disk.
Reprint the the levelling file and check the thickness again to confirm correct adjustment.
Repeat as necessary.

Printing and then adjusting using this method allows you to correctly and accurately adjust the bed to nozzle gap.
If you are printing with different size nozzles you can scale the part to suit.

description.text:
Bitcoin cold storage that's more durable than a paper wallet. Use the public address on top to receive Bitcoin. Flip the wallet open to spend with the concealed private key.  
The qr_models.py python script generates models from your own bitcoin address and private key.  See "Instructions" for more complete instructions.  
Note: That's not a real private key in the photo -- it's just a duplicate of the address. The address is real, however. Feel free to use it. :)

• OpenSCAD.

  • A printer that can print in two colors, or some way to color the top of the model black. I used an Afinia and changed the filament from white to black when the QR code started printing.

  • The qrcode and qr2scad python libraries: 

    `$ sudo easy_install qrcode`  
`$ sudo easy_install qr2scad`

  • The address and private key for a Bitcoin wallet, in text form. For example, to get the address and key from a MultiBit wallet:

    • Select "Request" and click the copy button next to the address to copy the address to the clipboard.
    • Select "Export private keys" from the "Tools" menu, check "Do not password protect export file, and click the "Export private keys" button. Then find the exported file and copy the private key out of the file.

description.header: To generate and print the stl files:
description.text:
• Save all of the files for this Thing in a directory.

  • Generate scad files for the QR codes by cd'ing to this directory and executing: 

    `./qr_models.py -k <private key> -a <address>`

  • Open btc_wallet_public.scad in OpenSCAD, choose "Compile and Render" from the "Design" menu, and then choose "Export as STL" from the Design menu. btc_wallet_public.scad includes the address QR code scad file generated by qr_models.py.

  • Print the STL, using white for the bottom portion and black for the upper layers that display the QR code. I recommend using ABS filament.

  • Open btc_wallet_private.scad in OpenSCAD. Repeat steps 3 and 4 for this file.

  • Snap the address plaque onto the private key plaque: align the bumps on the address plaque male joint with the grooves on the private key plaque female joint and press together.

  • Delete the private key export, key.scad, and the stl file for the private key plaque.

• Send Bitcoin to the wallet by scanning the Address plaque with Bitcoin wallet software. Hold the QR code under direct bright light when scanning.

  • If you have an Android phone, use the private key and the Mycelium app to spend from the wallet. Choose "Cold storage" from the Mycelium menu, click the "QR Code" button, and scan the Private Key plaque. Hold the QR code under direct bright light when scanning.

  • If you don't have an Android phone, import the private key into a software wallet, or transfer the entire balance to another wallet or account. See https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Paper_wallet#Redeeming_Keys_and_Withdrawing_Funds for tips on how to do this.

    IMPORTANT: Most wallet software does not support spending just part of the balance in a cold storage wallet. If you do not import the key into a software wallet or transfer the entire balance, you may lose any remaining balance. Mycelium does support partial spending from cold storage.

    • See https://bitcoin.org/ for more information about Bitcoin.

description.text: Funked Twisted Revolved is experimental art created by twisting and revolving shapes in Project Shapeshifter (by Autodesk). While it looks about the right size as a bracelet, the geometry makes it surprisingly uncomfortable. This experiment taught me how raw a real object can feel when curves are approximated using square or triangle faces, even small, rapidly rotating faces. Smoothness was not a goal for this print, but still a good lesson. I think it may help when designing in Sketchup and other vector-based tools. Just short of 30mm high, the curve is about 125mm at its widest point.

There's not much to mess with here: Just download and print. My advice is to try to use above-average quality filament. (I didn't but wish I had.) The picture showing the white filament also shows a few weak spots, even some blatant holes in the walls. Therefore I recommend you crank up the wall thickness and/or number of shells to avoid problems. Idea: A neat way to use this design might be to scale it down, print a bunch of them, and hook them together in a chain. These would make pretty interesting chain links, and scaling them down would smooth out some of the roughness it has at original scale. I don't recommend scaling it up very much; you'd be better off redrawing it in Shapeshifter.

description.text:
Simple tool to get hold of your watch when you want to open it.

My wife's Son needed a tool to open the backs of the special watches he collects.
The design is based on a tool that we saw at a cheap chinese webstore, since we didn't want to wait a month I built it myself with the addition of the vise holder. With in a few hours we could start opening the watches that wouldn't allow us to without this little tool. Offcourse you can buy it for cheap (approx $ 3.00 but this gives a lot more fun and proves again the usefullnes of your 3D printer.. ;-)

The used bolts are
1 Bolt M8x60 and Nut.
2 Allen screws M5x60 and 4 M5 nuts,
Enough springs that fit over the M5 allen screw. (i used 2 short springs on each side)
4 M4x20 Allen screw for the stands

Drill the big hole with 8mm to fit the M8,
Dril the other two holes to fit the M5 Allen screw, measure first.
Drill out the 4 or 8 top holes with a drill, a bit smaller than the M4 so you can tap them in.
Drill the 4 pins to fit the M4 allen screw.

I printed this little vise in Petg, this is nice and really strong. Printsettings for the Vise Clamps were approx 50% infill and 4 perimeters on all sides. The Vise holder was printed at a 30% infill with 2 solid layers for top and bottom and 4 perimeters on the sides

You need to print the vise and clamps 1 time, and you need 4 pins to print.

Yet another Replicator Foot.  Very similar to thing:23933 but it's not a derivative.  The self adhesive Gripper Pads on the foot appear to work extremely well.  The slots for the Replicator sides have small ridges in them that should help these feet remain in place.

no supports, no rafts, .27 layer height, 10% fill.
It prints fine with the slots down, and they are identical for all four feet.
The pads that fit in the bottom of the feet are one inch diameter, with adhesive backs.  It's a good high density foam with a good gripping surface, and I think I found them at either Walmart or Lowe's Hardware.  The exact brand is "SoftTouch by Waxman, #7385 Gripper Pads", 16/pkg.  You should be able to find that or something equivalent at just about any hardware/Megastore.
When installing, get the slots lined up and started on the sides, then shove down hard on the top corner of the Replicator.  The slight bumps that are in the sides of the slots should get a good grip on the plywood, and I'd be surprised if they ever came off without deliberate force.

title: Makerbot Filament Guide Ring and tube

description.text: After experiencing some printing problems with the Makerbot 2x that we have at the lab we were constantly trying to make it work better. I noticed that even though there was a tube guiding the filament to the extruder it kept getting out of place, hence not actually doing its job. So I measured our 3d Printer and designed these rings that keep the filament close to the wire tube giving them the required curve and angle to get inside the extruder properly and providing better movement around the printer following the movement of the extruders. Along with these I made a pair of small tubes that help the filament be pushed exactly at the middle of the extruder rather than being in tension. We have printed a total four of them and their doing their job just fine! Simple but necessary I think!

description.text:
An update to a previous project, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:572282. Wanted to make the room controller less intrusive in the room. I updated some of the hardware and eliminated others. As shown, it all fits into the previous 2 X 4 electrical box and uses a standard modern cover plate.

Below the display is a small vent with a mount for a Dallas Temperature sensor which I epoxy in place. The CPU tray included in the download section, is setup for a Pro-Mini clone which presses into place. I also have created a tray for a SPARK CORE / Particle Photon. Under the CPU tray between the I2C .96" OLED two color display is also a .5" X .5" push button switch for selecting options on the OLED.

I had to create a "Switch Bridge" for the back of the display because the back of the display is not flat. Components mounted on the back side of the display are of different heights. This caused the display to stick if pressed on the right side. The bridge corrects this. Please note the thickness here is critical, print only in .1 mm Layer Height.

Additionally another .5" X .5" push button switch is mounted just above the display with a pin hole to access, as a reset switch. At the top just above the reset switch is a slot for the 433 Mhz receiver. The switches I epoxy in place and use screws hold the CPU tray into place. Additionally the very top and bottom holes must be tapped using a 6/32 tap for the cover plate.

The pictures shown is the first one, and can use some serious wire management.

I do have a plate for the MicroView Display/CPU combo. Message me if interested. The MicroView works Very Well and is much easier to wire however, with the cost of the MicroView being $40, I chose to stay with the Pro-Mini and update to a two color OLED.

UPDATE: CPU tray for the Particle Photon has been added to the .stl files.

UPDATE: The OLED I use is the DIYMall display (Printed on the back on the display). It measures 1.062" by 1.062". I tried what appeared to be the same display directly from China but found their dimensions are 1.125 by 1.125" which will not fit.
